{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489749","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489749"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:28:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:28:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"734"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"734","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/734"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.12,0.55,0.09,0.24]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"734"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110342"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"734","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/734"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"734"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92613"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"1704"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7264"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7792"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13155"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110342","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110342"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old recent migrant from Turkey presents with a six month history of upper abdominal discomfort. He has lost 5 kg in weight during this time and his appetite has diminished. He has additionally developed a persistent cough over the past month with occasional blood-tinged sputum. He has chronic hepatitis B but is generally healthy and does not take any regular medications. He has a 30 pack-year smoking history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. His liver is palpable 2 cm below the costal margin. The rest of the examination is unremarkable. A CT scan is performed and a representative slice is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gallbladder cancer","Liver metastasis","Hepatocellular carcinoma","Hydatid disease","Hepatic tuberculosis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe CT scan shows a large heterogeneous hypo-attenuating mass with central necrotic foci in segment 4A of the liver. There is slight arterial enhancement of the capsule, and the mass causes slight bulging of the overlying capsule. These appearances are characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003Ehepatocellular carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E (HCC). This is consistent with the patient\u0027s history of hepatitis B and symptoms of abdominal discomfort, weight loss, and decreased appetite. The cough with blood-tinged sputum raises concern for potential metastatic disease to the lungs, which can occur with advanced HCC.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHCC is the most common primary liver cancer globally. Important risk factors include chronic hepatitis B and C infections, cirrhosis, and metabolic dysfunction-associated steatotic liver disease (MASLD).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELiver metastasis\u003C/strong\u003E must always be considered when liver lesions are identified, and the patient\u0027s respiratory symptoms could suggest a lung primary. However, metastases are usually more homogeneous than the lesion in this case and are often multiple, and the clinical timeline also makes this option less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGallbladder cancer\u003C/strong\u003E is rare, with risk factors including older age, female sex and gallbladder disease leading to chronic inflammation. It typically appears as a mass replacing the gallbladder fossa, often with direct invasion of adjacent liver parenchyma. The lesion in this image is located in the liver and does not appear to involve the gallbladder region.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven this patient\u0027s background from a region where \u003Cstrong\u003Ehydatid disease\u003C/strong\u003E is endemic, this condition must be considered. However, hydatid cysts are usually homogeneous (except when daughter cysts are present) and have a thin calcified rim, which is not seen in this image.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatic tuberculosis\u003C/strong\u003E may be considered given this patient\u0027s background and respiratory symptoms. It can present with focal lesions in the liver, but these are typically multiple, small, and have a miliary pattern. The large, solitary lesion seen here is not typical of hepatic tuberculosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hepatocellular carcinoma is characterised by the presence of a heterogeneous hypo-attenuating mass with central necrotic foci, rapid enhancement during the arterial phase, and rapid washout in the portal venous phase on CT imaging.","Risk factors for hepatocellular carcinoma include chronic hepatitis B or C infection, cirrhosis, and non-alcoholic fatty liver disease.","Hepatocellular carcinoma is the fifth most common cancer globally and the most common primary liver cancer."],"references":["Asafo-Agyei KO, Samant H. Hepatocellular Carcinoma. [Updated 2022 Jun 21]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92613"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"734"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18513"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18513","links":{"self":"https:/